<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 92 / Carrington sees no progress on Bosnia: London Peace Talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY and ROBERT MAUTHNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PEACE TALKS on Bosnia-Hercegovina made no progress in London yesterday but
negotiators will attempt to resume their efforts today.
Lord Carrington, chairman of the European Community-sponsored talks, said
last night the only significant aspect of the negotiations on the first day
was that leaders of the three ethnic groups turned up.
He said some constitutional settlement would have to be agreed between the
Moslem, Serb and Croat communities in Bosnia before any ceasefire could have
any meaning. 'The best way to get a ceasefire is to come to a constitutional
agreement which will render a ceasefire possible,' he said.
Yesterday there appeared little prospect that all three sides would sit at
the same table. After each had a separate meeting with Lord Carrington,
leaders of the three groups held separate talks with Portugal's Jose
Cutileiro, an EC mediator who chaired earlier Bosnian talks in Lisbon.
The Bosnian government representative urged the EC to place all heavy
weapons in Bosnia-Hercegovena under international supervision as a step
towards stopping the fighting. Mr Haris Silajdzic, Bosnia's foreign
minister, said ceasefires were meaningless unless steps were taken to disarm
the Serbs.
'How can we continue this peace conference when thousands of people are
being killed or deported, and regions are being ethnically cleansed by the
Serbs?' asked Mr Silajdzic.
He said the Bosnian government would reject the 'cantonisation' plan drawn
up by the EC last March. The plan was supported by Mr Radovan Karadzic, head
of the Bosnian Serbs, and Mr Mate Boban, head of Bosnia's Croats, because it
would eventually lead to the ethnic division of Bosnia between Croatia and
Serbia and leave the Moslems without a homeland.
Mr Karadzic, leader of Bosnia's Serbs and the Serb irregular forces, called
for a ceasefire and creation of a land corridor from the Adriatic port of
Split in Croatia to the Bosnian capital of Sarajevo, which is still under
siege by Serb irregulars.
Meanwhile, Mr Douglas Hurd, British foreign secretary, left for a four-day
tour of the Balkans. After talks in Paris with Mr Roland Dumas, his French
counterpart, he was due to visit Ljubljana, Zagreb, Sarajevo (if conditions
permit), Belgrade, Skopje and Tirana.
Mr Hurd is anxious to use the British presidency of the EC to boost efforts
to find a peaceful solution to the Yugoslav crisis.
</TEXT>
