<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 92 / Bonn sends warship to monitor UN embargo
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES, LAURA SILBER, NICHOLAS DENTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN, BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE German government yesterday ordered a destroyer and three reconnaissance
aircraft to join allied warships monitoring the UN trade embargo of Serbia
and Montenegro. Nato and Western European Union ships will begin monitoring
the coast of the former Yugoslavia today.
It is only the second time since the founding of the Federal Republic of
Germany that Bonn has ordered troops to a possible conflict area. The first
was during the Gulf war, when a squadron of German aircraft was sent to
Turkey to help protect it against Iraq. Bonn avoided an embarrassing summons
to the constitutional court by strictly limiting its armed forces' role in
the Adriatic to observation and intelligence gathering.
The German destroyer Bayern will not be allowed to stop suspect cargo
vessels or use force, Mr Klaus Kinkel, foreign minister, and Mr Volker Ruhe,
defence minister, stressed yesterday. It will also have to stay in
international waters. The German force's task was information-gathering on
behalf of the UN, not armed intervention. 'The object is to smother the war
in Yugoslavia,' added Mr Ruhe.
The cabinet decision, made in the face of opposition threats to challenge
the deployment in the constitutional court, marks an important step in the
government's plan to play a fuller role in international affairs. Both
ministers made clear the constitution, which in effect prevents German
troops from taking part in combat missions outside Nato territory, must be
altered as soon as possible.
The German move came as Serb forces stepped up attacks on the last Moslem
stronghold in eastern Bosnia, despite a pledge by the new Yugoslav premier,
Mr Milan Panic, to end the war in Bosnia-Hercegovina. Moslem fighters in
Gorazde broadcast an appeal for help as Serb forces continued to shell the
town, cut off for three months. 'Gorazde will cease to exist without
immediate help from outside,' the fighters said.
The bombardment of Gorazde appeared to put paid to chances that Mr Radovan
Karadzic, head of Bosnia's Serbs, and a close ally of Serbian president
Slobodan Milosevic, would support a ceasefire.
HINA, the Croatian news agency, said 31 people were killed and 61 wounded in
the attack on the town.
Some 50,000 people have sought refuge in Gorazde, normally a town of 20,000.
The siege has seen all phone and road links to the outside severed.
Across the border in Croatia 11 people were killed in a mortar attack on a
sports stadium housing refugees in Slavonski Brod.
At least 7,500 people have died in four months of fighting since Bosnia
gained independence, and some 1.2m people have fled their homes.
Mrs Sadako Ogata, UN High Commissioner for Refugees, yesterday called an
international conference on refugees as the exodus from Bosnia-Hercegovina
looked set to grow. Hungary and Austria, each with 50,000 refugees from the
former Yugoslavia, are to seek international backing for a security zone
within the former Yugoslav republics to protect victims of the conflict.
The two countries plan to put the proposal, whose idea is borrowed from the
operation to save the Kurds from the Iraqi regime, before the Hexagonale
group of central European countries this weekend. Hungary and Austria will
press the issue at the UN Security Council, where they are both members.
The International Red Cross has announced a central regional base in Hungary
for supplying refugee camps. Mr Peter Tjittes, regional head, said the
supply centre in southern Hungary would make costly deliveries of emergency
relief unnecessary.
</TEXT>
