<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 92 / Abu Dhabi blamed over BCCI: Draft Bingham report says vital
facts withheld from Bank of England
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ABU DHABI, the majority shareholder in the Bank of Credit and Commerce
International, has been criticised in the draft Bingham report for
withholding from the Bank of England vital information on the scale of the
fraud at the collapsed bank.
Lord Justice Bingham's inquiry into the collapse of BCCI highlights a
nine-month delay in communicating details of the huge losses and fraud -
including the theft of Dollars 2.2bn (Pounds 1.15bn) of Abu Dhabi's funds -
as a serious omission.
The criticism of the Gulf emirate's actions, in draft excerpts seen by the
Financial Times, forms one of the main conclusions of the 11-month
investigation by Lord Justice Bingham, which also assesses the roles of the
Bank of England and of Price Waterhouse, BCCI's auditor.
Abu Dhabi and its advisers are understood to be unhappy at what they see as
this slur on the emirate's reputation, and reject it. The Bank is also
braced for criticism of its role as supervisor of BCCI's UK operations.
Unless key passages of the preliminary report are revised or excluded from
publication, a row between Abu Dhabi and the UK government is expected to
follow the report's publication, which is not expected for several weeks.
In his draft, Lord Justice Bingham highlights an interview between Mr Swaleh
Naqvi, BCCI's former chief executive, and Abu Dhabi's representatives in
April 1990 - 15 months before the bank was shut down.
Lord Justice Bingham concludes that, had the contents of the interview been
communicated to the Bank of England by the emirate, a more detailed
investigation of BCCI and a more urgent programme for reconstructing the
bank might have been triggered. Alternatively BCCI could have collapsed or
been closed.
In the event, the Bank did not learn of the Dollars 2.2bn theft until the
end of February 1991.
But Abu Dhabi and its solicitors, Simmons &amp; Simmons, have argued to Lord
Justice Bingham that there is no evidence that the Bank would have behaved
any differently if it had received details of the Naqvi interview. The final
date for submissions to Bingham was last Friday.
One emirates' representative present at the controversial interview with Mr
Naqvi was Mr Ghanem al-Mazrui, head of Abu Dhabi's Department of Private
Affairs, which handles the personal finances of Sheikh Zayed, Abu Dhabi's
ruler.
In the conversation, Mr Naqvi gave the Abu Dhabi representatives details of
hitherto undisclosed losses at BCCI and said that Dollars 2.2bn of funds
belonging to Sheikh Zayed, had been stolen by ICIC Group, a Cayman Islands
offshoot of BCCI.
However, the Abu Dhabi representatives say the confession was confusing and
that they did not trust Mr Naqvi. They also believed ICIC was unrelated to
BCCI's core activities.
They were given no evidence to back up his assertions, though they
eventually received a three page hand written summary from Mr Naqvi of his
allegations, which they decided to investigate before communicating them to
outside authorities. It is not known whether they communicated details of
the confession to Sheikh Zayed.
No notes were taken of the conversation at the time. Lord Justice Bingham is
understood to have relied to a large extent on written evidence relating to
the discussion provided by Price Waterhouse which has passed on notes it
made during its investigation into BCCI under section 41 of the Banking Act.
However, Lord Justice Bingham is convinced that Abu Dhabi was not as
uncomprehending as it now says it was. His draft says that the Abu Dhabi
representatives were not financial innocents.
Bingham's report falls into three parts. The first contains the evidence and
is unlikely to be published. The second, of more than 300 pages, is a
narrative. The final section, which is still being prepared, contains Lord
Justice Bingham's conclusions.
The Bank of England and the Treasury, which commissioned the report, have
received the bulk of it already. The Government will then decide, in
consultation with the Treasury's solicitors, which parts to publish. The
Government has said that any parts likely to prejudice possible criminal
prosecutions will be excluded.
Creditors fail to get regulator's evidence heard, Page 8
Asset sales boost First American, Page 27
