FT  16 JUL 92 / World Commodities Prices: Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COFFEE prices recovered some of their recent losses at the London Futures
and Options Exchange, but traders said activity remained sluggish in the
absence of fundamental news. The September robustas position's Dollars 13
rise to Dollars 772 was 'on the back of New York', one explained. Dealers
said the potential for further advances was limited because several
producing countries were looking to sell at Dollars 10 to Dollars 20 above
present levels. The COCOA market also reversed its downtrend, with the
September position finishing at Pounds 597 a tonne, up Pounds 3 on the day,
about in the middle of the day's trading range. 'People are cautious at the
moment,' said one dealer, commenting on the low level of turnover. 'We're
waiting for origin news and anything out of the Geneva talks (on the
renegotiation of the moribund International Cocoa Agreement). At the London
Metal Exchange most metals reversed their recent downtrends. The exception
was TIN, which resumed the downward course that was interrupted on Tuesday.
Dealers attributed the Dollars 55 fall that took the cash position below the
Dollars 7,000-a-tonne mark to 'a negative technical outlook'.
Compiled from Reuters
