<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 92 / International Company News: CAE settles US military contract
suit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CAE Industries of Canada has settled for USDollars 55.9m a USDollars 231m
action filed by the US government against its CAE-Link subsidiary.
CAE-Link will pay USDollars 22.5m. BiCoastal of the US is responsible for
the balance.
CAE Industries, the world's leading commercial flight simulator builder, did
not admit liability in the case. The US Department of Justice claimed
CAE-Link, which specialises in military systems and training, overcharged
the government on contracts carried out between 1983 and 1988, and sought
triple damages.
Link was owned by the former Singer Corp at the time of the alleged
offences. CAE Industries bought Link in August 1988 and, in November 1989,
Singer filed for US Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection and became BiCoastal.
CAE maintained it did not know of any pending lawsuits when it bought Link.
The Justice Department, as part of the settlement, agreed CAE-Link did not
admit liability, legal fault or responsibility for the alleged offences.
Senior creditors led by the Royal Bank of Canada, and owed about CDollars
1bn (USDollars 800m), have agreed to exchange debt for stock in a new
company emerging from the restructuring of Central Capital, a fast-growing
financial services group.
</TEXT>
