FT  16 JUL 92 / International Company News: General Dynamics profits at
Dollars 65m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GENERAL Dynamics, the US defence contractor which is selling off peripheral
businesses, yesterday reported second-quarter earnings of Dollars 65m from
continuing operations, up from Dollars 33m in the same period of last year.
The 1991 figure excluded a Dollars 140m gain from a tax adjustment, which
pushed last year's income figure up to Dollars 173m.
The company sold its Cessna business aircraft operations in the first
quarter of this year, and is in the process of selling other businesses with
combined turnover of some Dollars 2bn.
It recently completed a tender offer in which it will spend Dollars 957m to
buy back shares from investors. The plan involves returning to shareholders
the excess cash being generated by the disposal programme.
The company's results from continuing operations worked through to earnings
of Dollars 1.48 a share, compared with 77 cents in 1991 without the tax
gain, and Dollars 4.06 with the gain. Sales in both periods totalled Dollars
1.6bn.
Earnings from the businesses up for sale, which are not included in
continuing operations, totalled Dollars 21m, compared with Dollars 38m a
year ago. However, the 1991 total included Dollars 17m from the now-sold
Cessna.
The company's tactical military aircraft operations recorded operating
earnings of Dollars 49m, up from Dollars 45m, while nuclear submarines made
Dollars 21m, compared with Dollars 20m; armoured vehicles Dollars 28m,
against Dollars 25m; and space launch systems made a reduced loss of Dollars
7m, compared with Dollars 25m.
The figures were also helped by the first-quarter retirement of Dollars 350m
in debt, with net interest outgoings of Dollars 12m last year becoming a
Dollars 7m inflow this quarter.
