<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Business Matters is devoted to one of the most important women in the
Philippines - neither Imelda Marcos nor Cory Aquino, but Elena Lim,
president of Manila's Solid Corporation. Her company produces cars,
televisions, plastics, and black tiger prawns which are exported to Japan.
David Lomax reports on how Elena Lim became a multimillionaire in a place
marked by poverty, corruption and political instability.
Can it really be 10 years since the death of pianist Andre Tchaikowsky? It
can, and Radio 3 marks the anniversary with three programmes, beginning
today (10.00) with recordings of him playing Chopin, Schumann, and his own
2nd string quartet.
Television's interest in Barcelona continues; presumably it will persist
until the Olympics. In Omnibus Special (10.20 BBC1) Robert Hughes visits
everyone from designers to transexual prostitutes, and talks to Monserrat
Caballe. Channel 4 begins a Spanish drama, Riders Of The Dawn (11.05) which
looked strikingly beautiful in competition at last year's Banff Festival.
</TEXT>
