<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 92 / Parcelforce faces imminent privatisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PARCELFORCE, the loss-making parcel delivery arm of the Post Office, is to
be privatised as soon as possible, Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and
industry secretary, said yesterday
Announcing the plans, Mr Heseltine emphasised there would continue to be a
universal parcel service at a uniform and affordable tariff.
'That is not negotiable,' he told MPs, indicating that the tariff would
remain a matter that ministers decided.
The government has yet to decide how privatisation is to be achieved, though
Mr Heseltine indicated that financial support would be made available so
that management and employees could make a bid.
Other potential bidders might include rivals United Parcels Service, TNT,
and Securicor.
Parcelforce has the leading 34 per cent share of ordinary parcel deliveries
but only 2 per cent of the premium 'next day' market.
Its turnover for 1991-92 was Pounds 508m and it sustained a loss of Pounds
24m.
Parcelforce management points to a profitable second half of the year and an
improvement from the losses of Pounds 131m in 1990-91.
Mr Heseltine said Parcelforce was the only part of the Post Office that
would be affected, but the decision prompted speculation that it would be
followed by moves to privatise the Royal Mail. The election manifesto said
only that the government was committed to maintaining a nationwide letter
service with delivery to every address in the UK with a uniform price
structure, and a national network of post offices.
Most post offices are already privately run.
Reaction from trade unions representing Parcelforce's 12,500 employees was
hostile, although Mr Terry Deegan, general secretary of the Communication
Managers' Association, said a management buyout 'might well be the least
undesirable privatisation option'.
The Union of Communication Workers, which represents the bulk of Parcelforce
workers, called for assurances on protection of the pension fund, job
security and continued union recognition. It also raised fears about the
future of rural parcel deliveries.
Sir Bryan Nicholson, the chairman of the Post Office, said his board
supported the government's view that privatisation would 'provide the
commercial framework and access to capital that Parcelforce needs'.
The operation would need 'continued significant investment' to secure a
strong future, he said.
Labour accused the government of indulging in 'privatisation for
privatisation's sake', and warned that the move threatened to undermine more
than 100 years of a universal parcel service.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-13004</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CGPA3AAXFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920716
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 92 / Virgin cancels launch of service
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
