<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 92 / An elite ranging from Branson to Papa Doc
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AS LIFE president of British Airways, Lord King will be joining a select
band of British executives and Third World politicians. But if precedent is
anything to go by, he cannot count on undisturbed enjoyment of his new role.
For politicians such as Dr Hastings Banda of Malawi or Papa Doc Duvalier of
Haiti, the title has not guaranteed popularity. Corporate life presidents
have been caught up in feuds with their successors; some have had to return
to sort things out.
Last year, Sir Laurie Barratt, life president of the house-building company
he founded, returned to the chair after the company suffered in the hands of
new managers.
Mr David Ogilvy, life president of Ogilvy &amp; Mather, was so distressed by the
bid for his advertising agency by Mr Martin Sorrell that he called the WPP
chief executive 'an odious little jerk'. Mr Ogilvy went on to serve as WPP
chairman.
Lord Kissin, life president of Guinness Peat, had a series of rows with Mr
Alastair Morton, whom he left in charge. Lord Kissin won, and Mr Morton
moved on to Eurotunnel.
A warning for Lord King came from Mr Alec Horsley, 89, life president of
Northern Foods. He said: 'I founded the firm. So many people knew me that I
couldn't really have been ignored. I don't think there will be quite the
same goodwill with Lord King.'
Other life presidents include Lord Bernstein of Granada, Sir Reo Stakis and
Lord Forte of the eponymous hotel chains, Lord Laing of United Biscuits and
Mr Richard Branson, life president of Virgin Music, now part of Thorn-EMI.
Mr Branson - whose other company, Virgin Atlantic, is suing BA - said
yesterday: 'It's probably sub judice to say it, but I wish Lord King well in
his retirement.'
</TEXT>
