<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 92 / Observer: Tiny's challenge
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Lord King's well-trailed decision to call it a day at British Airways and
hand over the control stick to Sir Colin Marshall raises the question of how
much longer that other entrepreneurial 74-year-old - Lonrho's Tiny Rowland -
is going to hang on.
It is nearly 20 years ago since the late Sir Basil Smallpeice tried, and
spectacularly failed, to unseat Tiny Rowland. Smallpeice, along with two
Conservative MPs - Duncan Sandys and Edward du Cann - had been one of three
non-executives appointed to the Lonrho board following growing City disquiet
about its financial affairs. However, Sandys and du Cann soon sided with
Rowland and although Smallpeice commanded a majority of Lonrho's directors -
the so-called straight eight - he and his supporters were booted out at the
next meeting.
If the battle were to be fought again, Rowland could have a fight on his
hands. Lonrho has cut its dividend and is selling UK assets to make ends
meet. The other big difference now is that unlike British Airways, Lonrho
does not have a sizeable cadre of non-executives to whom the chief executive
can turn for advice.
