<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 92 / Parliament and Politics: Manual workers press for new deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S 900,000 local authority manual workers, the poor cousins of the
public sector, are seeking a new deal from their employers as a quid pro quo
for providing services of the highest quality.
The two general unions, the TGWU and GMB, who yesterday lodged a joint claim
for Thursday's annual pay negotiations, implicitly recognise that the manual
workers are not going to improve their relative pay position.
The claim thus concentrates on non-pay issues such as harmonisation between
blue and white collar, an equality audit to root out discrimination, and the
claim for five days' training a year.
The two unions also propose 'single-table bargaining' - an idea which has
also been floated by the employers so has a good chance of being
implemented.
In a joint statement the two unions said: 'The 'them and us' culture in
local government has held manual workers back and not served the community
well.'
The manual workers have also asked for a substantial pay rise but are
unlikely to win more than 4 per cent. White-collar workers have settled for
4 to 4.4 per cent.
The electricians section of the AEEU engineering and electrical union will
have to reduce its full-time staff of 350 by between 35 and 50 to save
Pounds 1.3m a year. The savings are required by a continuing reduction in
members, by the ending of a pension 'holiday' and by the probable
requirement of TUC affiliation fees.
</TEXT>
