FT  15 JUL 92 / Parliament and Politics: Concession over fishing limit
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT last night bowed to Tory backbench pressure over plans to
limit fishermen's days at sea, promising parliamentary consultations on
fishing quotas.
The Commons announcement of the concession from Mr David Curry, fisheries
minister, averted a threatened rebellion by Conservative MPs opposed to the
proposals in the Sea Fish (Conservation) Bill.
There was cross-party support for an amendment introduced during the report
stage by Mr Neville Trotter (Cons, Tynemouth), demanding that the government
should return annually to parliament for approval of the days-at-sea limits
it intended to set.
But Mr Curry gave MPs an assurance that the Commons and the Lords would be
consulted before any reductions in days at sea were introduced after 1993.
The Bill was later given a third reading by 311 votes to 282, a government
majority of 29.
It now goes to the House of Lords.
</TEXT>
