<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 92 / Parliament and Politics: Tory revolt over MPs' allowances
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN and IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT suffered a resounding defeat last night when a full-scale
Conservative backbench rebellion overturned its efforts to limit a rise in
MPs' office expenses to Pounds 4,000.
As Mr John Major, the prime minister, looked on, a crowded chamber stayed up
into the early hours of the morning to vote by a overwhelming majority of
131 to authorise a rise of Pounds 11,000.
The vote came despite the government austerity drive that last week held
down senior civil service increases to 4 per cent instead of a 20 per cent
figure recommended by the Top Salaries Review Baord.
The scale of the government defeat - by 317 votes to 186 - clearly shocked
senior ministers on the Treasury frontbench and party business managers.
It will also severely undermine efforts to set an example to the country at
a time when business is attempting to rein-in wage bills.
Advocates of the higher office expenses insisted during an impassioned
debate that the rise was not a salary increase for MPs, but merely an
overdue rise, needed to ensure their office staff could handle ever-rising
workloads.
Nonetheless, the jubilant reaction to the government's defeat on both sides
of the House constitutes a serious embarrassment at a time when tightened
belts are the official order of the day.
Defending the government's proposal to restrict the rise in allowances to
9.8 per cent, Mr Tony Newton, the leader of the House, accepted that
workloads had increased.
But he added: 'Many other individuals are being asked to accept pay
restraint or find it necessary to impose it on themselves.'
A succession of MPs countered, however, that the call for restraint amounted
to efforts by the executive to restrain legislators' abilities to serve
their constituents and keep checks on the government.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
