<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 92 / British Rail White Paper: Politicians send the trains down
yet another track
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT may seem an obvious question, but if the private sector is better at
running railways than the state, why were they nationalised in the first
place?
British Rail is a relatively recent creation. From the opening of the
Stockton &amp; Darlington railway in 1825 to nationalisation in 1948, all of
Britain's railways were built and owned by the private sector.
Far superior in speed to canals and horse-drawn transport, railways
flourished in the 19th century. They spread to all corners of the kingdom,
and most paid good dividends to shareholders.
Almost from the start politicians wanted to play trains, too. They
interfered over service levels and fares alike.
While the railways prospered they were able to tolerate a degree of
political interference. But by the turn of the century they were having to
cope not only with increasingly onerous regulation of freight charges, but
with labour unrest and heavy losses of passenger traffic to buses and trams.
When the First World War began in 1914, it put the railways under immense
strain. It also brought them under state control, and many influential
voices argued that they should stay that way when the war ended.
Instead an attempt was made to restore viability by merging the 120 private
companies into four: the Great Western, the London Midland &amp; Scottish, the
London &amp; North Eastern, and the Southern.
Although these companies enjoyed virtual monopolies over large areas, none
of them succeeded in making much money. Competition from motor vehicles was
increasing; labour troubles resumed; the government continued to regulate
passenger fares and freight charges; and the Depression brought a slump in
demand.
During the Second World War the railways came under even greater strain than
during the first - this time suffering physical destruction as well as
increased wartime demands. Again the state took control. By the time the war
ended the railways were in such a poor state that nationalisation was almost
taken for granted. It duly took place in 1948.
After the failure of two post-war efforts to restore prosperity - the 1955
Modernisation Plan and the Beeching rationalisation of the 1960s - it seemed
that the arrival of motor transport had ended the profits potential of
railways for good. That might have marked the end of the private sector's
interest in them were it not for the arrival of the Thatcher government in
1979.
An inveterate privatiser, and notoriously hostile to public transport, Mrs
Thatcher declared as early as 1982 that she wanted to see BR sold off. Given
the size of BR's enduring losses, however, the government had to recognise
that this was impractical in the short-term. Instead it told BR to
concentrate on becoming more efficient and turned its back on BR's pleas for
higher investment, contenting itself in the meantime with the privatisation
of other transport sectors such as road freight, aviation and buses.
What changed matters was the upsurge in demand during the economic boom of
the late 1980s, and the property boom, which left BR awash with development
profits, giving rise to the belief that it could conceivably have a
commercial future after all.
Starting with Mr Paul Channon in 1988, successive transport ministers avowed
their enthusiasm for privatisation. The only question was how to achieve it,
given the precarious nature of BR's profits and the need for massive
investment to compensate for years of underfunding.
Privatising BR in one great lump seemed out of the question. Apart from
anything else, it was almost inconceivable that anyone would want to buy it.
By the time Mr Malcolm Rifkind took over as transport secretary in November
1990, the options had narrowed down to ways of splitting it into attractive
parcels.
Within a year Mr Rifkind had drawn up his master plan. The profitable
InterCity and Railfreight sectors would be sold outright, while the
loss-making Network SouthEast and Regional Railways operations would be
franchised out. He failed, however, to carry his cabinet colleagues with
him. Trade and industry ministers argued that a separate track authority was
necessary to create competition between train operators, while Mr John
Major, the prime minister, was said to hanker for a return to the days of
four regional railway companies.
In the end all the options were undermined as the economy sank deeper into
recession. BR's profits fizzled out and hopes of finding a buyer for any
part of the railway evaporated.
After months of embarrassing delays, a general election and yet another
change of transport secretary, the result was the watered-down version that
emerged yesterday - a long way from the full-blown privatisation that Mrs
Thatcher had dreamed of a decade earlier.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
