<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 92 / British Rail White Paper: Government abandons full-scale BR
sell-off - Emphasis will be on improving rail services / Franchise authority
will award contracts to private sector
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE white paper on the future of British Rail starts by acknowledging that
the corporation cannot be sold off to the private sector like other public
utilities, whether in one great lump or in parts. Its losses are simply too
big.
So there will be no stock market flotation or trade sale of BR. Instead the
corporation will go on running the railways indefinitely, but attempts will
be made to improve the quality of services by creating more opportunities
for the private sector to operate trains.
The first step will be to split BR into two. One part, to be named
Railtrack, will own the track, signalling and other infrastructure, and
charge for its use. The other part - presumably still called BR - will run
the trains.
The government will then try to get the private sector interested in taking
over train operations. The freight operations will be sold outright, but on
the passenger side the government hopes to contract-out train services
through franchises.
A franchise authority will be created to carry out the franchising on the
government's behalf. The government will decide what grants will be
available for subsidising loss-making services, and will set broad
objectives for service levels, quality and fares. The authority will then
hold open competitions among private companies to see which offers the best
terms for taking the contracts.
Beyond these broad principles, however, the government seems to have little
idea about how the franchises will work in practice. The white paper does
not spell out what franchises will be available, when they will be offered
or how long they will last. Everything, apparently, is negotiable: it all
depends on what the private sector is interested in doing.
The white paper is also hazy about how private companies are to obtain their
trains and drivers. Ideally, it suggests, it would like them to buy or lease
trains, but it recognises that such an obligation could be a barrier to
entry. So it concedes that most franchisees will want to use BR's existing
trains, and these will be available to rent.
InterCity services get a special mention in the white paper. The government
believes that some of these are close enough to profitability to be sold.
But it also recognises that this will not happen in the lifetime of the
present parliament. In the meantime, therefore, these will be franchised on
a so-called 'line-of-route' basis, such as the East Coast Main Line from
London King's Cross to Edinburgh or the Midland Main Line from London St
Pancras to Sheffield.
The passenger-services section of the white paper observes that BR staff are
likely to be keen to bid for franchises as well as the private sector. The
government is not only prepared to accept such bids, but intends to
encourage them by offering help with legal and financial advice.
Also worth noting is that Railtrack will receive no subsidies. It will have
to make a living - and pay for infrastructure investment - out of charges to
train operators. The level of charges is a severe bone of contention with
would-be train operators, but the white paper ducks it.
Instead it is to be the subject of a separate report by Coopers &amp; Lybrand,
the accountants, later this year.
On the freight side, the government's targets are more ambitious. It sets a
goal of getting all the freight and parcels businesses privatised in the
course of the present parliament, but again it is thin on detail. It
suggests that the freight businesses would be more likely to find buyers if
they were split up into their constituent parts. For example, users of the
coal, metals, construction materials and petroleum trainload services might
be interested in buying and running these business. Distribution companies
might be interested in other parts of the business, as might BR's own staff.
The white paper does not address the contentious issue of what will happen
to BR's loss-making freight services. If all rail freight is to be
privatised within the present parliament, the implication is that the
unwanted services will close - hardly an environmental plus for
privatisation.
In addition to the franchising of BR's existing services and the sale of the
freight operations, the government hopes to get new services on to BR's
tracks by opening access to any would-be operators who can meet required
standards. But as the white paper acknowledges, the lack of spare capacity
on BR's busier tracks will limit the scope for this, as will arguments about
how much different types of passenger and freight services should be charged
for using the infrastructure.
Some of these rows will be sorted out by an official regulator, a body to be
set up independently of the franchise authority.
The regulator's job will be to ensure fair play between operators over
rights of access.
The white paper also says the private sector could run stations. Some might
be rented to franchisees, and others sold or leased.
Safety issues, like so much in the white paper, are to be the subject of
further study, though it is stressed that these are of paramount importance.
Closure procedures will remain unchanged, and there is a commitment to
maintaining a single timetable and compatible ticketing. And there is one
item calculated to endear the white paper to BR's staff: 'Concessionary
travel arrangements for employees, and their dependants, and for retired
staff will also be safeguarded.'
New Opportunities for the Railways: the Privatisation of British Rail. Cmmd
2012, HMSO. Pounds 5.40.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
