<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 92 / Cable technology rules eased
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGO DIXON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CABLE television industry is to be freed from regulations which detail a
preferred technology for the construction of cable networks.
The move, announced yesterday by the Department of Trade and Industry and
Oftel, the telecommunications regulator, is intended to reduce costs and
boost investment in the industry.
It marks a retreat from the government's policy in the early 1980s of using
cable TV to bring high-technology services into people's homes.
The government wanted to encourage operators to build networks using a
technology called 'switched star' architecture by offering 23-year licences
instead of the normal 15 years.
The aims were to back a British technology and to promote advanced services
such as video-conferencing, tele-shopping and telebanking.
But nearly two thirds of the industry opted for the cheaper 'tree and
branch' technology. Moreover, the main customer demand has been for TV and
basic telephone services rather than advanced services.
Yesterday's decision is designed to allow operators to determine for
themselves, on the basis of commercial considerations, the best technology
to use. It brings the cable TV industry into line with the government's
policy of taking a technology-neutral approach to telecommunications.
Oftel is to remove the detailed technical requirements on operators with
23-year licences. The DTI has also decided to increase to 23 years the
licences of operators with 15-year licences to put both types of operator on
the same footing.
Mr Bill Wigglesworth, acting director-general of Oftel, said the move would
boost investment in the already growing telecommunications sector.
Mr Nick Mearing-Smith, executive group director of Nynex UK, one of the main
cable industry players, said it was 'an excellent decision'.
</TEXT>
