<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 92 / Producer price rise stabilises in June
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INFLATION as measured by prices of manufactured goods at the factory gate
failed to show a decline last month, dashing hopes of a let up in cost
pressures.
The Central Statistical Office said yesterday the prices of products leaving
factories rose 3.6 per cent in the year to June, the same as in May. This
measure is often used as the underlying 'core' inflation indicator.
Between May and June, the index of producer prices rose 0.1 per cent to
137.4. Year-on-year inflation at the factory gate remained at its lowest
level since April 1987, a reminder of how demand pressures have been
squeezed inthe recession.
But added to evidence of continuing inflation was the 3 per cent price
increase of goods excluding food, drink and tobacco in the 12 months to
June, compared with 2.6 per cent in the previous month.
The year-on-year increase for goods excluding edible items and tobacco - the
prices of which can move erratically due to excise duty changes - was the
biggest since January.
Last month's higher-than-expected figures may have been affected by large
price falls in specific manufactured items in June last year, distorting the
year-on-year comparison.
In June this year the price index of factory goods excluding food, drink and
tobacco also rose 0.1 per cent. Prices of minerals rose 0.4 per cent, while
those of scientific instruments and chemicals increased 0.3 per cent and 0.2
per cent respectively.
The prices of manufacturing raw materials and fuels rose a seasonally
adjusted 0.4 per cent after a fall of 0.5 per cent in May.
</TEXT>
