<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 92 / Blue Arrow jury had 'understood the issues'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE is no evidence that the length or complexity of the year-long Blue
Arrow fraud trial caused the jury any difficulty, the Court of Appeal was
told yesterday, John Mason writes.
Mr Nicholas Purnell QC, who brought the prosecution for the Serious Fraud
Office, told the court that all the available evidence, notably questions
asked by the jury throughout the trial, demonstrated they had understood the
issues involved.
Mr Purnell defended his decision to maintain a large indictment against the
defendants - a move defence lawyers have alleged led to the trial becoming
unmanageably and unfairly large.
Mr Jonathan Cohen, Mr David Reed, Mr Nicholas Wells, all former County
NatWest executives, and Mr Martin Gibbs, a former UBS Phillips &amp; Drew
director, are appealing against their convictions of conspiracy to defraud.
The appeal continues.
</TEXT>
