<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 92 / Manufacturing shows surprise fall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A DROP in the production of cars, chemicals and materials for the building
industry caused a surprise fall in UK manufacturing output in May, adding to
doubts over the prospects for economic recovery.
Contrary to City expectations of unchanged production, the Central
Statistical Office yesterday reported that manufacturing output declined by
0.6 per cent in May compared with April. Output of the energy and water
industries fell by 2.2 per cent in the month, to result in a 0.9 per cent
drop in overall industrial production.
The seasonally-adjusted data for May were further evidence that Mr John
Major's election victory failed to boost economic activity. Figures for the
latest three months, which the government considers a better guide to recent
trends, painted only a marginally better picture. The CSO puts the latest
estimate of trend growth in manufacturing output at 0.5 per cent a year.
Manufacturing output between March and May was 0.6 per cent higher than in
the previous three months, but 0.9 per cent lower than in March to May last
year.
Reflecting the vagaries of North Sea maintenance activity, energy output in
March to May was down 3.1 per cent compared with December to February, but
2.7 per cent up on the year before when the repairs to the Piper Alpha oil
field were being completed.
Overall industrial production was 0.4 per cent lower in the latest three
months compared with December to February, but unchanged compared with March
to May last year.
In manufacturing, yesterday's statistics showed a 0.7 per cent increase in
consumer-goods output between the two latest three-month periods, while
production of investment goods grew 0.2 per cent and output of intermediate
goods dropped by 1.1 per cent.
The metals, engineering and allied industries, textile and clothing and
'other manufacturing' industries, which include paper and publishing,
increased their output by about 1 per cent in the March to May period
compared with December to February. Food output was unchanged while drink
and tobacco production rose by 1.3 per cent.
Chemicals, a strong performer last year, showed a 0.5 per cent drop in
output between the two three-month periods. In spite of a fall in production
in May, car output between March and May was 7.4 per cent higher than over
the previous three months.
</TEXT>
