<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 92 / ITV's choice for top job turns it down
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ITV network last night again began the search for a chief executive
after the candidate who was offered the job turned it down.
The offer of the most important job in commercial television, managing a
Pounds 500m-a-year budget, went to Mr David Arculus, group managing director
of Emap, the fast-growing magazine, newspaper and exhibitions group.
Mr Arculus, who is 46 and earns about Pounds 160,000 a year, has been in
discussions with ITV for the past few weeks and was formally offered the job
on Friday. He considered the possible move over the weekend and then told
ITV on Monday that he had decided not to leave Emap. ITV executives believed
Mr Arculus was about to accept.
Mr Arculus worked briefly for the BBC World Service but has been at Emap for
the past 20 years and has been a key figure in taking it from being a small
family-owned regional newspaper group to its present capitalisation of more
than Pounds 460m.
The ITV job was worth about Pounds 230,000 not including fringe benefits,
but would also have been one of the highest-profile jobs in British
television.
Mr Arculus was chosen by ITV after more than 70 names had been produced by
head-hunters. He was not offered any more money to stay but decided he could
not bear to leave.
ITV's failure to attract its man is a serious blow. The new commercial
television franchises begin in January with four new broadcasters and
negotiations are already under way with the Office of Fair Trading on the
shape of the future ITV network.
ITV urgently needs a chief executive to run what will be a new centralised
system of commissioning programmes for the ITV network from both ITV
companies and independent producers.
Immediately beneath the chief executive will be a senior
commissioner-scheduler who will have considerable influence on what is shown
on ITV.
