<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 92 / Banks report sharp rise in police alerts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BANKS and other UK financial institutions are alerting the police about an
increasing number of transactions by their depositors, according to figures
released yesterday by the British Bankers Association.
The association said details of an estimated 12,000 suspicious transactions
or depositors would be passed this year to the police National Criminal
Intelligence Service. This compares with the 6,000 last year and 3,000 in
1990.
Mrs Sue Thornhill, assistant secretary of the BBA responsible for security
and fraud, said the growth in the number of reports reflected a heightened
awareness on the part of banks of the need to report any suspicion of
criminal activity.
Detailed guidelines for banks and building societies on reporting suspicions
of money laundering were drawn up by the BBA three years ago after the House
of Commons Home Affairs select committee criticised the Bank of England for
doing too little in advising financial institutions about their
responsibilities under the law.
The guidelines were issued to cover disclosure requirements under the Drug
Trafficking Offences Act 1986, the Criminal Justice Act 1988 and the
Prevention of Terrorism Act of 1989. The Criminal Justice Act contains
provisions protecting banks from potential breaches in client
confidentiality.
While money laundering is still not in itself an offence the drug
trafficking and terrorism legislation made it illegal to launder or to
assist in the laundering of the proceeds of terrorism and drugs.
Banks formerly reported to the National Drugs Intelligence Unit, which was
absorbed in April into the NCIS, the police group responsible for collating
intelligence on all serious and organised crime.
Direct reporting to the NCIS gives the police access to all suspicious
banking transactions coming through the BBA-organised system.
Mrs Thornhill said counter staff were encouraged under the guidelines to
report unusual or suspicious transactions within their banks. These reports
were filtered through in-house fraud departments or officers and only if
suspicions still remained were they passed on to the police.
The new reporting requirements had brought changes to the banks.
Mrs Thornhill said: 'The banks have never wanted crooks on their books. In
the past when something suspicious has happened they have looked at an
account and closed it down. Now they have to report the account.'
Under existing laws, only individuals can be prosecuted for money laundering
offences but institutions themselves will soon become liable under an EC
directive on money laundering which must be implemented by all member states
by January 1 1993.
</TEXT>
