FT  15 JUL 92 / Jakarta set to close file on Timor killings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM KEELING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JAKARTA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Indonesian military yesterday handed President Suharto the results of
its own investigation into the massacre of civilians in the disputed
territory of East Timor last year, writes William Keeling in Jakarta.
The report is likely to signal the government's determination to close the
incident which caused many international donors to express concern.
An earlier report organised by the government said about 50 people had been
killed in the incident, as against an estimate of up to 180 by independent
witnesses.
Most international donors, who meet in Paris this week to consider aid to
Indonesia for the year ahead, expressed their satisfaction with the first
report and are expected to pledge about Dollars 4.8bn to Indonesia, a
similar sum to last year.
Yesterday's report says that only 18 graves have been discovered. An armed
forces spokesman conceded, however, that some of the 66 people still missing
are believed dead.
