<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 92 / London talks 'last chance'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE leader of Bosnia's Serbs, Mr Radovan Karadzic, yesterday said
EC-sponsored talks due to open in London today could be the last chance for
peace and called on the United Nations to police a green line between the
warring factions, Reuter reports.
Mr Karadzic blamed Bosnian Moslem leaders for violating ceasefires in
Sarajevo but said he was willing to meet them and Croatian leaders at the
talks in London. He hoped the talks would achieve 'an unconditional
ceasefire - then let us talk for 10 months if it is necessary, but without
any more killing.'
Mr Karadzic said he would welcome more UN monitors or peace-keeping forces
to police all of Sarajevo, not just the airport where they are now, and to
separate the warring forces. 'I would like the (UN) mandate . . . for the
whole area of the city of Sarajevo and . . . I would suggest a green line
between the sides in the conflict,' he said.
He said he believed that all sides to the conflict might now understand that
there could be no winners. 'I do hope that all three sides are aware that
this may be the last chance for peace.'
Mr Karadzic hoped the EC talks would lead to a formal resumption of the
peace negotiations suspended in May by Bosnia's Moslem leaders in protest at
a Serb mortar attack in Sarajevo which killed 16 people and injured 110.
British officials said yesterday that Lord Carrington would have separate
talks with Mr Karadzic, Bosnian foreign minister Haris Silajdzic, and Mr
Marte Boban, a leader of Bosnia's Croat community.
Peace talks that Lord Carrington held in Sarajevo earlier this month failed
and were followed by one of the worst upsurges in fighting since the siege
of the city began.
</TEXT>
