FT  15 JUL 92 / World Commodities Prices: Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COCOA prices at the London Futures and Options Exchange fell sharply
yesterday, continuing the downturn that began on Monday morning. As
speculators and investment funds unloaded holdings the September delivery
price tumbled to Pounds 594 a tonne at the close, down Pounds 22 on the day
and Pounds 38 from the 2 1/2 -month peak reached on Monday. Traders
suggested, however, that the market was likely to consolidate at around the
present level, which was still Pounds 85 above the 16 1/2 -year low reached
nearly three weeks ago. At the London Metal Exchange COPPER and TIN prices
made modest gains from Monday's closing levels but other metals lost further
ground. And copper's rise of Pounds 9.25 in the three months position was
mainly a reflection of sterling's weakness. In dollar terms, the price was
down slightly from Monday's final kerb close. Tin prices were boosted
earlier by a wave of short-covering following the falls of the three
preceding trading days. After drifting back later the three months price
closed at Dollars 7,077.50 a tonne, up Dollars 25 on balance. NICKEL
remained easier after investment fund liquidation, the three months price
closing at Dollars 7,442.50 a tonne, down Dollars 72.50 on the day.
