FT  15 JUL 92 / International Company News: Federal Express delivers Dollars
113.8m loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FEDERAL EXPRESS, the largest overnight package delivery business in the US,
suffered a Dollars 113.8m loss after tax in the year to end-May.
The loss was scored on revenues down from Dollars 7.69bn a year earlier to
Dollars 7.55bn. FedEx, which has been incurring heavy losses from its
international operations recently, made a small Dollars 5.9m profit after
tax in 1990-91.
However, in the previous year it reported a Dollars 115.8m surplus after
tax, and Dollars 184.6m in 1989-90.
In the fourth quarter of 1991-92, Federal said the overall after-tax profit
totalled Dollars 35.8m, up from Dollars 31m in the same period a year
earlier.
But its international business remained in the red - although the operating
loss from this division fell to Dollars 53.2m, on revenues of Dollars
536.1m, against a deficit of Dollars 74.6m on revenues of Dollars 633.5m a
year earlier.
In March, FedEx announced a withdrawal from the highly-competitive European
delivery industry, sub-contracting all its intra-European delivery business
and laying off more than 6,000 employees.
This move, according to Federal, has succeeded in removing more fixed costs
than revenue, thus aiding profitability. Express package volumes to and from
Europe had been maintained at levels 'ahead of expectations'.
Mr Fred Smith, Federal's founder and chairman, warned that further
improvement would 'require a continuation of growth in international express
package volumes and higher profit ability from international air freight
business'.
For 1991-92 overall, the loss from the Memphis-based company's international
operations totalled Dollars 612.9m, compared with a Dollars 419.1m deficit
in the previous 12 months.
The former figure, however, was scored after Dollars 254m of restructuring
charges, largely to cover the withdrawal from Europe. The 1990-91 loss came
after charges of Dollars 121m.
On the domestic front, where Federal Express carries about half the nation's
overnight express packages, FedEx said the climate remained extremely
price-competitive.
Despite this, Federal managed an operating profit margin of 12.2 per cent,
which it attributed to productivity gains and cost improvements.
</TEXT>
