FT  15 JUL 92 / Letter: The Church and its finances
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr OLIVER LEVER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Before readers of your delightful article on the Church's missing
millions (July 11) reach for their cheque books, may I point out that the
figure of Pounds 12,000 as the pay of the clergy is misleading?
In December 1982, the Church Commissioners, in a memorandum to the General
Synod, estimated that a vicar was better off with his stipend of Pounds
5,802, plus his tax-efficient perks, than if he were to be paid Pounds
10,500 only, with no housing. Adjusting for inflation, the perks therefore
now seem to be worth Pounds 8,099 making, with the average stipend of Pounds
12,800, a total of Pounds 20,899. In the interim, interest-free loans have
been made available for car purchase.
Oliver Lever,
Blackacre,
Back Lane,
Malvern, Worcs WR14 2HJ
