<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUL 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow stages recovery from
early decline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
AMID conflicting pressures, US share prices posted modest gains in thin
trading yesterday as markets staged a recovery from early losses linked to
weakness in bond prices and the dollar, writes Patrick Harverson in New
York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was ahead 6.75 at 3,337.31,
while the Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was slightly firmer on balance at 414.87, up
0.25. The Nasdaq composite put in the day's best performance, rising 2.42 to
570.22.
Turnover on the New York SE was a meagre 149m shares, while rises outpaced
declines by 978 to 738.
Overnight losses on foreign markets combined with continued weakness in the
dollar, linked to speculation that the Bundesbank may raise German interest
rates; and these two with declining bond prices as the 30-year benchmark
bond fell  1/2 point, pushing the yield back up to 7.67 per cent. All of
this undermined early sentiment but some positive quarterly earnings reports
helped prices recover by mid-morning.
Bank stocks were a feature amid a string of well-received figures, although
most of the early gains were erased later in the session by profit-taking.
JP Morgan, after advancing more than Dollars 1 on news of a sharp rise in
second-quarter profits from Dollars 231m a year ago to Dollars 385m, settled
back to end unchanged at Dollars 61 5/8 .
Chase Manhattan had an early rise but fell later to finish down Dollars 1
1/4 at Dollars 27 7/8 in active trading, after the bank reported a net
profit of Dollars 152m in the quarter, up from Dollars 132m at the same
stage of 1991.
First Chicago moved in a similar pattern, gaining ground before closing a
net Dollars  5/8 off at Dollars 35 7/8 , having reported second-quarter
profits of Dollars 68.2m, up 17 per cent from a year earlier.
Also in financials, Federal National Mortgage Associ ation (Fannie Mae) rose
early on, but ended down Dollars  3/4 at Dollars 63 3/4 in turnover of more
than  1/2 m shares, after news of record three-month profits of Dollars
402m, compared to Dollars 382m in the previous quarter.
Alcoa firmed Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 73 1/2 after the company reported a
second-quarter loss of Dollars 30.6m after taking charges of Dollars 104.7m
related, among other things, to employment reductions.
IBM put on Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 97 7/8 on news that the computer group
had entered an alliance with Siemens, of Germany, and Toshiba, of Japan, for
the joint development of advanced semiconductor products.
On the Nasdaq market, Spartan Motors plummeted Dollars 6 7/8 to Dollars 13
5/8 in heavy trading after the company warned that second-quarter earnings
would come in between 28 and 34 cents a share, well below market
expectations.
Century Medicorp jumped Dollars 3 1/4 to Dollars 19 after stating that it
was negotiating the terms of a stock swap acquisition by another, as yet
unnamed but larger, healthcare company.
Canada
TORONTO stocks closed steady after a day of light trading activity. The TSE
300 index edged up 1.7 to 3,449.2 and advancing issues led declines by just
272 to 244. Volume came to 18.9m shares.
The real estate group posted the day's biggest decline, 1.91 per cent. One
of the sub-group's most heavily weighted stocks, Cambridge Shopping Centres,
fell CDollars  3/4 to CDollars 15 1/2.
</TEXT>
