FT  14 JUL 92 / International Company News: US sales at Visa climb by 11.5%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
VISA, one of the leading US credit card companies, said its first-quarter
results showed an 11.5 per cent increase in domestic sales volume.
The San Francisco-based company claimed this was superior to the average 10
per cent growth rate for other large credit card companies during the first
three months of 1992.
The statistics are set against the backdrop of a perception by most
economists that US consumer confidence remained weak during the opening
months of the year.
Visa said it recorded Dollars 40.7bn in card transactions for the quarter
ended on March 31. The number of Visa cards in circulation in the US rose by
4.5 per cent to 143m cards. The number of Visa transactions in the US
increased by 9 per cent.
