<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUL 92 / International Company News: Alcoa in red after Dollars 104m
charge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING, Mining Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALUMINUM Company of America (Alcoa), the world's biggest aluminium company,
plunged to a loss of Dollars 30.6m, or 37 cents a share, in the second
quarter. The decline followed after-tax charges totalling Dollars 104.7m, or
Dollars 1.22 a share.
The charges also pushed Alcoa's first-half earnings down 74.5 per cent from
Dollars 178.2m, or Dollars 2.09 cents, to Dollars 45.4m, or 52 cents.
The company maintained it had done reasonably well, considering the turmoil
in the industry and low aluminium prices, to be able to report earnings of
Dollars 74.1, or 85 cents, before charges in the second quarter. In the same
months of 1991, net earnings were Dollars 81.2m, or 95 cents.
Although sales in the second quarter fell from Dollars 2.57bn to Dollars
2.41bn, shipments were up from 659,000 tonnes to 706,000 tonnes. In the
first half, sales slipped from Dollars 4.98bn to Dollars 4.66bn while
shipments totalled 1.37m tonnes, against 1.34bn in 1991.
Although aluminium prices were substantially lower in the quarter, the
impact was mostly offset by a fall in costs, a favourable tax rate, and
reductions in finance costs.
The second-quarter charges included Dollars 44.9m (Dollars 65.9m before
tax), or 52 cents, for redundancy payments. Alcoa said recently it would
reduce its world-wide workforce of 65,000 by 2,100 this year.
There is also an extraordinary charge of Dollars 50.2m, or 59 cents, for the
previously-announced redemption of high-cost debt to reduce financing costs,
and a charge of Dollars 9.6m, or 11 cents, paid to US hourly employees to
extend labour contracts by one year.
This is the second time in six months Alcoa has been hit by substantial
charges. In the fourth quarter of 1991 it suffered charges of Dollars 217m
relating to the cost of environmental clean-ups and restructuring.
</TEXT>
