<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUL 92 / Arts: Twelfth Night
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID MURRAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHAT the English Shakespeare Company mostly does is to tour, so Claire
Lyth's trappings for its Twelfth Night are coolly plain and adaptable. A
floor of green and gold tiles, some pretty, spidery screens, tall panels of
curtains; moody lighting by Michael Bogdanov does the rest.
Michael Pennington's production pretends not to be a 'production' at all,
just the play itself played straight, with everything coming from the words
 -and the songs too, which have a sharp dramatic point. Pennington tips his
hand in a programme-note: he has definite, even tendentious readings of
Shakespeare's characters and their situations. The players stick loyally to
his recipes, and the net effect is a tonic: fresh, unblinking, direct.
At some points it narrows the range of feeling in the comedy; but Twelfth
Night has inexhaustible possibilities, and the specialised view here is
quite happy enough to be going on with.
Jenny Quayle's Viola (who speaks the verse better than anybody) is concerned
with the 'lost' Sebastian, her twin and spirit-double. Whenever she
remembers him, she grips one's heart - and after their rapt reunion, they go
off embracing each other rather than their new partners.
Her attraction to Michael Mueller's Orsino is an unexplained accident, and
her romantic debacle with the gender-blind Olivia a minor inconvenience.
Allie Byrne's Olivia is a crisp estate-manageress. For most of the play she
deals with Viola-'Cesario'-Sebastian as with a raw junior. Like her
gentlewoman Maria (Tracey Mitchell), she grows shrill in vehement passages,
and her grip on the verse slackens.
Malvolio (Timothy Davies) owes a great debt to John Cleese, but repays it
with interest. Derek Smith's Uncle Toby is tough and truculent, more sour
than roguish; Colin Farrell's jesting Feste offers authentic music-hall,
practised routine with dead eyes.
As for Sir Andrew Aguecheek, James Hayes' comic-cuts costume and wig make
him a simple ass. The role of Clown has been redistributed, to the advantage
of Sean Gilder's wry, friendly Fabian. Alan Cody brings a welcome, salty
breath of passion to Antonio.
For Sebastian himself, Vivian Munn's funny, boyish face and shy gaucherie
twin him nicely with Viola, but scotch the virile contrast he should make.
Richmond Theatre, box office (081)940 0088. In repertory to July 18.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
